The error in your screenshot means Vercel needs you to prove you own focusflow.com before it can connect your app. This usually happens if the domain was used with a different account or project previously.

To fix this, you need to log in to your domain registrar (like GoDaddy, Namecheap, or Google Domains) and update your DNS Records as follows:

  1. Prove Ownership (TXT Record): Add a new record of type TXT. Set the Host/Name to _vercel and the Value to the long string in your picture (vc-domain-verify=focusflow.com,942c8512...).

  2. Point to Vercel (A Record): Your current A record points to 216.198.79.1, which is incorrect. Edit it and change the IP Address to 76.76.21.21.

To find your free domain name on GitHub, follow these 3 steps:

  1. Open your Repository (the project folder) on GitHub.

  2. Click the Settings tab (the gear icon ) at the top.

  3. On the left sidebar, click Pages.

At the top of that page, you will see a banner that says:

"Your site is live at https://your-username.github.io/your-repository-name/"

Important Tips:

  • The Pattern: Your free domain will always look like: https://[Your-GitHub-Username].github.io/[Project-Name]/.

  • Wait for the checkmark: If you just uploaded your files, it might take 12 minutes for the link to appear. Look for a green checkmark next to the link.

  • Make sure it's Public: GitHub Pages only offers free hosting for Public repositories (unless you have a Pro account).

Since you're using GitHub Pages, make sure your main file is named exactly index.html in the main folder, otherwise the link will show a "404 Not Found" error!

To make your repository public so you can use GitHub Pages for free, follow these steps on the GitHub website:

  1. Open your Repository on GitHub.

  2. Click the Settings tab (the gear icon at the top).

  3. Scroll all the way down to the bottom of the page to the "Danger Zone".

  4. Click the button that says "Change visibility".

  5. Select "Make public".

  6. GitHub will ask you to confirm by typing your repository name (e.g., your-username/focusflow).

  7. Click "I understand, make this repository public".

You can find your domain in your GitHub Settings, and yes, you can change part of it for free!

1. Where to find it

  1. Open your repository on GitHub.

  2. Click the Settings tab (the gear icon at the top).

  3. On the left-hand menu, click Pages.

  4. Your domain will be shown in a box at the top (usually starts with https://[your-username].github.io/...).

2. How to change it (for free)

Since you aren't paying for a custom domain, you can't change the .github.io part, but you can change the text at the end of the URL by renaming your repository.

  • Option A: Rename the project
    If your repo is named focusflow, your link is yourname.github.io/focusflow. If you rename the repo to myschoolapp, your link becomes yourname.github.io/myschoolapp.

    • Go to Settings > General.

    • Change the Repository name at the top.

  • Option B: The "Special" Shorter URL (Highly Recommended)
    If you want your link to be as short as possible (no slash at the end), rename your repository to exactly: [your-username].github.io.

    • Example: If your username is SuperStudent, rename the repo to SuperStudent.github.io.

    • Your link will then be: https://SuperStudent.github.io/

If you can't see the link yet, it's usually because GitHub is still "building" your site or you haven't picked a branch.

Here is exactly where to look and what to do if the link is missing:

1. The "Magic" Link Location

Settings (Top bar ) Pages (Left side menu )

2. If the link is missing (Fix this):

Make sure your settings look like this:

  • Source: Change "GitHub Actions" to "Deploy from a branch" (this is easier for beginners).

  • Branch: Select main (or master).

  • Folder: Select /(root).

  • Click SAVE.

3. Wait for the "Yellow Dot"

After you click Save, go back to the main page of your repository. You will see a small yellow dot () next to your last commit name. Wait about 60 seconds until it turns into a green checkmark (). Once its green, the link will definitely be waiting for you in the Settings Pages tab.

The reason you see a blank page is because browsers (like Chrome or Safari) cannot read .tsx files directly. They need to be "built" (compiled) into regular JavaScript first.

To fix this, we need to add a GitHub Action. This is a small script that runs automatically every time you save your code. It will build your app and fix the blank screen for you.

1. How to fix the Blank Page

I am adding a new file called .github/workflows/deploy.yml. Once you save this into your repo:

  1. Go to your GitHub repo.

  2. Look for the Actions tab at the top. You'll see a yellow "dot" running.

  3. Wait for it to turn into a Green Checkmark .

  4. Refresh your link! It should work.

2. How to change the name

To change the "domain" name (the part after github.io/):

  1. On GitHub, click the Settings tab (the gear icon at the very top).

  2. The first box you see is Repository name.

  3. Type your new name there and click Rename.

  4. Important: After renaming, you might need to wait 2 minutes for the link to update.

Yes, you can definitely deploy to Netlify! Many developers actually prefer it over GitHub Pages because it handles the "Blank Page" issue much more easily and gives you a free .netlify.app link that you can change whenever you want.

Why Netlify is great for "JustStart":

  1. Easy URL Changes: You can change your site name (e.g., my-cool-app.netlify.app) in 2 seconds without renaming your GitHub repo.

  2. No Blank Pages: It automatically handles the build process perfectly.

  3. Environment Variables: It has a very simple place to paste your Gemini API_KEY so it stays secret.

How to do it:

  1. Go to Netlify.com and sign up with your GitHub account.

  2. Click "Add new site" -> "Import an existing project".

  3. Select your GitHub repository.

  4. Important: In the "Environment Variables" section, add a key named API_KEY and paste your Gemini key there.

  5. Click Deploy.

I've added a netlify.toml file to your project. This is a "magic" file that tells Netlify exactly how to run your app so you never get a 404 error or a blank screen.

I understand exactly what's happening. You are seeing two different things:

  1. The Wrong Website: You manually added focusflow.com as a custom domain in Netlify. Since you don't own that domain, Netlify is trying to send people there, but a different company's page shows up.

  2. The Blank Page: Your actual app at juststart-educational.netlify.app is blank because it needs to be re-deployed now that you've added the API Key.

How to fix the "Wrong Website" (focusflow.com)

  1. Go to your Netlify Dashboard.

  2. Click on your project (juststart-educational).

  3. Click Site configuration (left menu) -> Domain management.

  4. Scroll down to Custom domains.

  5. You will see focusflow.com listed. Click the Options button next to it and select Remove domain.

  6. Now, Netlify will only show your correct link: juststart-educational.netlify.app.

How to fix the "Blank Page"

After you add the API_KEY in Netlify, the app doesn't automatically "know" it's there until you build it again.

  1. In your Netlify project, click the Deploys tab at the top.

  2. Click the blue button that says Trigger deploy.

  3. Select Clear cache and deploy site.

  4. Wait 1 minute for it to finish. Refresh your page, and the blank screen will disappear!

  5. Finally, click Options > Remove domain on focusflow.com. It will work now!
